[White "Chapter 1"]
[Black "9...exd4 / 9...Bb7 / 9...Re8"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C91"]
[Annotator "IM Renier Castellanos"]
[PlyCount "73"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. d4 exd4 $6 {Black can hardly fight for equality with this premature
capture.} (9... Bb7 10. Nbd2 {standard idea of Nf1 and Ng3 and now two clear
ideas which I think you must remember:} Re8 (10... exd4 11. cxd4 Nb4 12. Qe2 $1
{best move in my opinion} c5 13. a3 Nc6 14. dxc5 dxc5 15. e5 Nd5 16. Ne4 {
with an initiative. White is playing Bg5 with Nd6 ideas, also Bc2 with
possibilities to attack on the kingside.} c4 (16... Nc7 17. Bg5 $16) 17. Bc2
$16 {Neg5 is coming next}) 11. Ng5 $5 (11. Nf1 {is possible}) 11... Rf8 12. Nf1
Na5 13. Bc2 Nd7 14. Nf3 Nc4 15. Ng3 g6 16. a4 Bf6 17. Bh6 Re8 18. b3 Ncb6 19.
a5 Nc8 20. Qd2 $16 {Duda, J (2666)-Hamitevici, V (2468) Drancy FRA 2016 Both
sides can improve here, but this is one example of how White can save a tempo
skipping the move h3. Overall I think that if Black accepts these positions, White
has already won the opening battle.}) (9... Re8 {more flexible than 9...Bb7
since Black keeps the option of Bg4'} 10. Nbd2 (10. Ng5 Rf8 {is not much of
anything for White since there are no useful moves right now}) 10... Bf8 (10...
exd4 11. cxd4 Bg4 {could be the critical line} 12. Nf1 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Na5 14.
Bc2 c5 15. d5 {I prefer White here. He will play b3 to keep the knight away
from c4 and use his strong center. This needs practical tests}) 11. Nf1 h6 12.
Ng3 {White has completed his development saving a full move on h3, perhaps it
is not much, but a move is a move!} exd4 ({on} 12... Bg4 {it is interesting
for White to try} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 {with idea of f4}) 13. cxd4 Bg4 14. Be3
(14. h3 $5 {would be my choice} Bxf3 15. gxf3 Na5 16. Bc2 c5 17. d5 g6 18. b3
Bg7 19. Rb1 {White's plan is Kg2-f4 where the two bishops and strong center
should provide a good advantage.}) 14... Na5 15. Bc2 Nc4 (15... c5 {is more
active} 16. h3 $1 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nc4 18. dxc5 dxc5 19. Rad1 Qa5 20. Nf5 {
with complications difficult to evaluate}) 16. Bc1 c5 17. b3 Nb6 18. Bb2 cxd4
19. Bxd4 Rc8 20. Rc1 $14 {Felgaer,R (2587)-Perez Candelario,M (2498) Andorra
2004}) 10. cxd4 Bg4 ({I also considered the move} 10... d5 11. e5 Ne4 {This
position is identical to the one that arises in the Anti-Marshall with the
exception that here Black has lost a tempo. If you search this position in
your database, you will find hundreds of games with Black's move with balanced
results. This is a better version for White.} 12. Nbd2 (12. Nc3 Nxc3 13. bxc3
Bf5 {is playable but less clear}) 12... Nxd2 (12... Bf5 13. a3 {planning to
continue with Bc2 next and force the capture on d2. Black will have some
problems with the c file.} (13. Bc2 Nb4 14. Bb1 c5 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Bxe4 Bxe4
17. Rxe4 Qd5 18. Qe2 Nc6 19. dxc5 Bxc5 20. b3 $14 {is also possible})) 13. Bxd2
Bg4 14. Qc2 $1 Nb4 (14... Bxf3 15. Qxc6 $18) 15. Qc3 Bf5 16. Red1 Rb8 17. Be3 (
17. Ne1 {immediately is better. Followed by Rac1} Rb6 18. Rac1 Nc6 19. Qe3 a5
20. h3 $16) 17... Rb6 18. Ne1 a5 19. a3 Nc6 20. a4 Bb4 21. Qc1 bxa4 22. Bxa4
Ne7 23. Nc2 Qb8 24. Nxb4 Rxb4 25. Qc5 {was much better for white in Smeets,J 
(2617)-Zelbel,P (2432) Dortmund GER 2016}) 11. Nc3 b4 (11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 {
gives White a strong center plus the bishop pair} Na5 13. Bc2 c5 14. dxc5 dxc5
15. e5 Nd7 16. Qd3 (16. f4 $16) 16... f5 17. Qd5+ Kh8 18. Rd1 Ra7 19. e6 Nb6 {
Polzin,R (2491) -Nikolic,P (2602) Germany 2010} 20. Qxd8 Bxd8 21. Bxf5 $16) 12.
Nd5 Rb8 13. Ba4 {White has a wide choice of good continuations here, really
there is no need to get too in depth in this position'} ({the usual
Castellanos,R: 'the routinary'} 13. Nxe7+ Qxe7 14. Ba4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Na7 16.
Bg5 h6 17. Bh4 g5 18. Bg3 Nh5 19. Rc1 {gives White a super simple game and a
better position.}) 13... Nxd5 14. Bxc6 Nb6 15. Bf4 $16 d5 16. Rc1 (16. exd5 $16
Bd6 17. Be5 f6 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Qb3 Rbd8 20. Nd2 Nxd5 21. Rac1 {Black has big
problems}) 16... dxe4 17. Rxe4 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Bg5 19. Rc5 Bxf4 20. Qxf4 Qd6 21.
Qe5 (21. Qc1 $5) 21... Nd7 22. Qxd6 (22. Bxd7 {was the simplest} Qxd7 23. Rxc7
Qa4 24. Rxf7 Rxf7 25. Qxb8+ Rf8 26. Qe5 Qxa2 27. d5 Qb1+ 28. Re1 Qf5 29. Qd4
$16 {with a clear advantage although Black is not without chances.}) 22... cxd6
23. Bxd7 dxc5 24. dxc5 g6 25. Kf1 a5 26. Rd4 Rfd8 $6 (26... Kg7 {was a better
defense}) 27. c6 Ra8 28. Ke2 Kg7 29. Kd3 Ra7 30. Rd5 Rc7 31. Kd4 Ra8 32. Kc5
Raa7 33. Kb6 b3 34. axb3 Kf8 35. Rxa5 Rxa5 36. Kxa5 Ke7 37. Ka6 {1-0 (37)
Kamsky,G (2671) -Lenderman,A (2431) Philadelphia 2006} *

