1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. d4 Bg4 10. d5 Na5 11. Bc2 c6 12. h3 Bh5 {This move should be taken
seriously as it has been played by several strong players, including Carlsen.}
13. dxc6 Qc7 (13... Nxc6 {has the drawback that the knight here does not
control the d5 square} 14. Bg5 Qb6 (14... h6 {helps White in his plan.} 15.
Bxf6 (15. Bh4 $5 {could be tried as well. White does not need to go for the
immediate capture but the text move is just fine.}) 15... Bxf6 16. Nbd2 Rc8 17.
Nf1 Na5 (17... b4 $5 18. Ng3 (18. Ne3 bxc3 19. bxc3 Ne7) 18... Bg6 19. c4 {
looks like a Sveshnikov Sicilian. The position is equal I would say but White
has a good control of the center.}) 18. Ng3 Bg6 19. Qe2 Qc7 20. Rad1 Rfd8 (
20... Nc4 21. Bb1 Rfd8 $11) 21. Bb1 Qb6 22. Nf1 Nc4 $6 (22... Qc6 {by keeping
the pressure on e4, Black makes it difficult for White to bring his knight to
d5. Then White should try} 23. N3h2 {followed by Ng4}) 23. b3 $1 {a very nice
idea to keep in mind} Na3 24. Bd3 {White sacrifices a pawn but manages to
bring his knight to d5 which fully compensates for the material deficit.} Rxc3
25. Ne3 $44 b4 26. Nd5 Qc5 27. Bxa6 Nc2 28. Rf1 Rxf3 $2 (28... Nd4 29. Nxd4 (
29. Nxf6+ gxf6 30. Nxd4 exd4 $13) 29... exd4 30. Qg4 $14) 29. Qxf3 $18 Bg5 30.
Qg4 Nd4 31. h4 f5 {Sturua,Z (2602) -Jenni,F (2399)/Biel 1999 and here White is
just winning with} 32. Qg3 f4 33. Qg4 Bxe4 34. hxg5 Bxd5 35. gxh6 Qc7 36. Rxd4
exd4 37. Re1 {the attack is decisive}) 15. Nbd2 Rad8 16. Qe2 {this move
prevents the idea of d6-d5} Nd7 (16... d5 $2 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. exd5 Rxd5 19.
Qe4 $18) 17. Be3 Qb7 18. a4 b4 19. a5 $14) 14. Nbd2 Qxc6 (14... Rad8 $5 {
has the idea of d6-d5 without even capturing on c6!} 15. Nf1 d5 $5 16. exd5
Nxd5 (16... Rxd5 17. Qe2 Nxc6 18. Bb3 $142 $1 Rdd8 (18... Rd7 19. Ng3 Bg6 20.
Nxe5 $16) 19. Ng3 Bg6 20. Nxe5 Nxe5 21. Qxe5 Bd6 22. Qg5 $14 {Black has some
compensation but a pawn is a pawn}) 17. Qe2 Bf6 (17... Nxc6 18. Ng3 Bg6 19.
Bxg6 hxg6 (19... fxg6 {is an ugly capture but Black hopes to gain some active
play.} 20. Ne4 ({but definitely not} 20. Nxe5 Bc5 $36) (20. a4 $5 {is also
quite strong because it weakens Black's queenside.}) 20... h6 21. a4 $1 Qb7 22.
axb5 axb5 {Tal,M-Dely,P/Miskolc 1963} 23. b4 Kh7 24. Be3 $16) 20. Nxe5 Rfe8 21.
Nxc6 Qxc6 22. Qf3 $16) 18. a4 $142 $1 {This helps shaking Blacks queenside and
develops our a1-rook.} Nc4 19. axb5 axb5 20. Bb3 Ndb6 (20... Qxc6 21. Nxe5 Nxe5
22. Qxh5 $16) 21. Ng3 Bg6 22. Ne4 $16 {White will gain the bishop pair next.})
15. Nf1 Bg6 (15... Rfe8 16. Ng3 Bg6) (15... Rfd8 16. Ng3 Bg6 17. a4 $5 {
[%csl Yb5]} (17. Nh4 $6 {is premature because of} d5 {Vitolinsh,A-Arutiunov,A/
Soviet Union 1967}) 17... Nc4 18. Qe2 $14 {with ideas like Bd3 next}) (15...
Nc4 16. Ng3 Bg6 17. a4 Rad8 {the plan is to achieve d6-d5 in the near future} (
17... Nb6 {is strongly met with} 18. a5 $5 Nbd7 19. Nh4 Nc5 (19... d5 20. Nhf5
$36 {[%cal Rc1g5,Gd1f3]}) 20. Nhf5 $14) 18. axb5 {it's logical to take now
since Black has abandoned the a-file.} axb5 19. b3 Nb6 20. Bb2 $14 {with the
idea of Bd3 and Qe2 is good and solid enough} (20. Bd2)) 16. Ng3 Rfe8 17. a4 $1
Nc4 18. Qe2 {Standard play from White - he wants to follow with Bd3 next.} (18.
Nh4 $5 {can also be tried with the idea of Qf3 and Nf5} d5 19. Nxg6 hxg6 20.
exd5 Nxd5 21. Be4 (21. Qf3) 21... Rad8 22. axb5 axb5 23. Qf3 Qe6 24. Ra8 Rf8
25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. Rd1 Nc7 $11) (18. Bd3 Bf8 19. b3 (19. Qe2 d5 $1) 19... Nb6 {
looks acceptable for Black.}) 18... d5 (18... Bf8 19. Nh4 d5 20. Nxg6 hxg6 21.
axb5 axb5 22. Rxa8 Rxa8 23. Bd3 $5 $11 {/+/=}) 19. exd5 Nxd5 (19... Qxd5 20.
axb5 axb5 21. Rxa8 Rxa8 22. Bxg6 hxg6 23. Nxe5 $14) 20. Bxg6 hxg6 21. axb5 axb5
22. Nxe5 Nxe5 23. Rxa8 Rxa8 24. Qxe5 b4 {Black based his counterplay on this
move and in the game it worked but it seems that White could have made things
more difficult for the young Carlsen.} 25. Qe4 $6 (25. cxb4 Bxb4 26. Rd1 $14)
25... bxc3 26. bxc3 Qxc3 27. Rd1 Rd8 $11 {now the game is dead equal} 28. Ne2
Qb4 29. Qc2 Nf6 30. Rxd8+ {½-½ (30) Naiditsch,A (2626) -Carlsen,M (2548)
Warsaw 2005} *

