1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. d4 Bg4 10. d5 Na5 11. Bc2 c6 12. h3 Bxf3 {This capture is nothing great
for Black but still White must know how to play correctly to seize the
initiative.} 13. Qxf3 cxd5 14. exd5 Nc4 {bringing the knight back into the
game is the most logical move but let's look at some alternatives:} (14... Rc8
15. Nd2 Nc4 (15... g6 16. b4 Nc4 17. Nxc4 Rxc4 18. Bd2 Nh5 19. Bd3 Rc7 20. a4
f5 {Tseshkovsky,V (2550)-Beliavsky,A (2530) Ashkhabad 1978 and now White could
have obtained a large advantage with} 21. axb5 e4 22. Qe3 exd3 23. bxa6 $1 {
the pawns are stronger than the piece}) 16. Nxc4 bxc4 (16... Rxc4 17. a4 $16 {
Black's queenside pawns are weak}) 17. b4 $14) (14... Qc7 15. b3 (15. Nd2 Nc4
16. Nxc4 Qxc4 17. Bd3 Qc7 18. a4 Rab8 19. Rd1 g6 20. axb5 axb5 21. Be3 Rb7 22.
Ra6 $14) 15... g6 {Vogt,L (2495)-Pinter,J (2445) Kecskemet 1977} 16. Bh6 Rfc8
17. a4 b4 18. c4 Nb7 19. Nd2 a5 20. g4 $1 $14 {The position resembles the
King's Indian. I think that White can slowly prepare an attack on the kingside.
}) 15. Nd2 Nb6 (15... Nxd2 $6 {This move does not pose any problems for White
at all. That being said, White must put an effort to make the best of his
positional advantage.} 16. Bxd2 Qc7 (16... Rc8 17. b4 $5 Qb6 18. a4 Qb7 19. Bb3
Bd8 {Sax,G (2535)-Nikolov,S (2419)/Ljubljana 2004 and now I like} 20. Qe2 {
with the idea of answering} Bb6 {with} 21. a5 Ba7 22. c4 $16) (16... g6 17. a4
Qb6 18. b4 (18. Ra3 $5 {is a nice idea to put pressure on b5 by means of Bd3
and Rb3}) 18... Qb7 19. Bb3 Nd7 20. c4 bxc4 21. Bxc4 f5 {Spoelman,W (2428)-Van
der Wiel, J (2483)/Hilversum 2007} 22. Rac1 {with the idea of b4-b5 soon. The
two bishops and the passed pawn give White the advantage.}) 17. a4 (17. b4 $5 {
would be imprecise because of} a5 $1 $13) 17... b4 (17... Qb7 $5 18. Bg5 h6 19.
Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Qf5 Rfd8 21. Re4 $16) 18. a5 $1 {a nice move enabling White to
improve the light-squared bishop via a4-square.} bxc3 19. Bxc3 $16 Qc4 (19...
Qb7 20. Ba4 $5 (20. Red1 $5) 20... e4 21. Qg3 Qxd5 22. Bc2 $1 {the threat is
Be4 or Re4} Nh5 23. Qg4 Nf6 24. Bxf6 Bxf6 25. Bxe4 $18) 20. Bd3 (20. Red1 $5)
20... Qc5 (20... Qb3 $2 21. Bxe5) 21. Rac1 $1 $16 {Romanishin,O (2610)-Nikolic,
P (2620) Jugoslavija 1991}) (15... Rc8 {transposes to 14...Rc8} 16. Nxc4 Rxc4 (
16... bxc4 17. b4) 17. a4) 16. Nf1 Qc7 {Let's have a look at the alterantive:}
(16... Nbxd5 17. Ng3 {White has lost a pawn but the compensation is obvious.
He has a strong bishop pair. Furthermore, the queen and knight all deployed on
the kingside is always something Black should worry about. The pawn is rather
useless, for now.} Nc7 (17... Re8 18. Nf5 Bf8 19. Bb3 (19. a4 $5 {is yet to be
tried}) 19... e4 20. Qg3 Qd7 21. Nh6+ Kh8 {Negi,P (2480) -Inarkiev,E (2625)
Ermioni 2006 and now White can improve with} 22. Be3 $1 $16 {with the idea of
Bd4}) 18. Nf5 $5 {I like this direct approach} (18. a4 $5 {is also interesting
and has been played in other games}) 18... Ne6 19. a4 b4 (19... bxa4 $5 20.
Rxa4 $14) 20. Qb7 $1 {[%csl Yb4,Ye7] with a double attack on e7 and b4} Re8 21.
Qxb4 $14 {once the pawn is recovered, White can be happy as he keeps all the
pluses.} Bf8 22. Qh4 g6 23. Nh6+ Kg7 (23... Bxh6 24. Bxh6 $16) 24. a5 Be7 25.
Qg3 Nh5 26. Nf5+ Kh8 27. Qf3 {In this game Adams plays with an extreme
precision} Bg5 (27... Nhf4 28. Nxe7 Rxe7 29. Be3 $16) 28. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Rd6]}
Qf6 29. Nxd6 Qxf3 30. gxf3 Bxc1 31. Raxc1 $16 {White is clearly better
although he failed to convert his advantage and the game was eventually drawn.
Adams,M (2707)-Nikolic,P (2596)/ Enschede 2006}) (16... Ne8 {this is a serious
move for Black - ideas like g7-g6, f7-f5 or Bg5 are in the air. I think White
must react in the most energetic way with} 17. a4 $1 {and now:} bxa4 (17...
Nxa4 18. Bxa4 bxa4 19. Re4 $1 {key move in my opinion} f5 (19... a3 20. Rxa3
Bg5 21. Bxg5 Qxg5 22. Rb4 Qc1 23. Qe3 Qb1 24. c4 $14 {Tseshkovsky,V (2550)
-Zakharov,A (2435) Moscow 1976}) 20. Rexa4 Nc7 21. Rc4 {with idea of Rc6 and
c4 with a positional advantage}) 18. Ng3 $5 {has scored better than 18.Bxa4
but to me both moves are strong} (18. Bxa4 Nxa4 19. Rxa4 f5 20. c4 Qc8 21. Qa3
Nf6 22. Bg5 Nxd5 23. Bxe7 Nxe7 24. Qxd6 $16 {Chandler,M (2390)-Sharif,M (2380)
Wellington 1978}) 18... g6 19. Bh6 Ng7 20. Bxa4 Nxa4 21. Rxa4 f5 (21... Qb6 22.
b4 Rfc8 23. Rea1 f5 {Tseshkovsky,V (2550)-Beliavsky,A (2530) Tbilisi 1978} 24.
Qd3 e4 25. Qf1 $16 Qb7 (25... Rxc3 $2 26. Rxa6 Rxa6 27. Rxa6 $18 {Qa1 next})
26. Rxa6 Rxa6 27. Qxa6 Qxa6 28. Rxa6 Rxc3 29. b5 $16) 22. Rea1 Bg5 23. Bxg7
Kxg7 24. Rxa6 Rxa6 25. Rxa6 Qe7 26. c4 Rc8 27. Qc3 Bf6 28. Qa5 Kh6 29. Rc6 {
White had a winning position in Adams,M (2707)-Nisipeanu, L (2693) Montpellier
2006}) (16... g6 $5 {this move has been played by the strong grandmasters
Saric and Guijarro. It's similar to the mainline. Black has a solid Najdorf
structure and is planning to fight for the initiative on the dark squares.} 17.
Bh6 $1 Re8 18. a4 (18. Ng3) 18... Qc7 (18... Nxa4 19. Bxa4 bxa4 20. Rxa4 Qd7
21. Rea1 Qb5 22. Ne3 e4 $1 (22... Qxb2 $2 23. Nf5 $1 {with a strong attack}
gxf5 $4 24. Qg3+ Ng4 25. Rxg4+ fxg4 26. Qxg4+ Kh8 27. Qg7#) 23. Qd1 Qxb2 24.
Qd4 {this is a complex position in which White has a full compensation for the
material but it's quite double edged. One sample line could follow} Nh5 25. g4
$1 Bf6 26. Qd1 Ng7 27. Nc4 Qxc3 28. R1a3 Qd4 29. Qxd4 Bxd4 30. Rxa6 Rxa6 31.
Rxa6 {and White gets his pawn back with good chances to win.}) 19. axb5 axb5
20. Bd3 Rxa1 21. Rxa1 Nbxd5 22. Ne3 Nxe3 23. Bxe3 d5 24. Bxb5 $14) 17. Ng3 {
White goes to f5. There are alternatives but no need to deviate from this move}
g6 18. Bh6 Rfc8 (18... Rfb8 {is another logical move for Black.} 19. a3 {
is my preference} (19. Re2 {with similar ideas as in the main game} Nbd7 (19...
Nc4 20. Bb3) 20. Bg5 $5) (19. Rad1 {and now} Ne8 (19... Nbd7 $5 {is considered
main move in this position and now I propose} 20. a3 {keeping the tension} a5
21. Bg5 Ra7 (21... b4 22. Ba4 $1 $14 {improves the bishop}) (21... Qd8 $5 22.
h4 $5 $13) 22. h4 $13) 20. Nf5 $5 (20. Re2) 20... Bf8 (20... gxf5 21. Qxf5 $18)
21. Qg3 Ng7 $1 22. Nxg7 Bxg7 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24. h4 {Chandler,M (2515)-Nikolic,P
(2669) Dresden 2008 and now Black would have been better with} h5 $1 $15) (19.
h4 $5 {is a move that deserves attention. With all of black pieces on the
queenside it makes sense to start actions against the black king. This needs
practical tests}) 19... Ne8 (19... Nbxd5 $2 20. Bb3 $16) (19... Nfxd5 $2 20.
Be4) 20. Rad1 Nc4 21. Bc1 Ng7 22. Qe2 f5 23. Nf1 {with a tense game. White can
consider a3-a5 followed by Bd3 ideas or maybe even g4 at some point. The
position is level.}) 19. Bb3 {Maybe 19.Rad1 is more precise when White would
have the retreat to c1 whenever it is needed. For example:} (19. Rad1 Qd8 (
19... Nc4 20. Bc1 $13) (19... b4 20. Bf5 $1 bxc3 21. Bxc8 Rxc8 22. bxc3 $14 {
it is not so easy to convert but White is clearly better.}) (19... Nfd7) 20. h4
$13 {Polgar,J (2630)-Nikolic,P (2645)/ Monte Carlo 1995} (20. a3 $142 $5)) (19.
h4 $5 {deserves attention as well. For example:} Qd7 $2 (19... b4 $6 20. Bf5 $1
Rcb8 (20... gxf5 21. Nxf5 $18 {the attack is just winning}) 21. cxb4 Nbxd5 22.
Be4 Nxe4 23. Nxe4 $14) 20. Bf5 $1 gxf5 21. Nxf5 Rc4 22. b3 Rg4 23. Bg5 Rxg5 24.
hxg5 Nfxd5 25. c4 Nb4 26. c5 {The end of a forced variation that leaves White
with a winning position} dxc5 27. Rxe5 Bf8 28. Nh6+ Kh8 29. Rd1 N4d5 30. Rdxd5
Nxd5 31. Rxd5 Qc6 32. Nxf7+ Kg8 33. Nh6+ Kh8 34. Nf7+ Kg8 35. Ne5 Qe6 36. Ng4
Rc8 37. Nf6+ Kh8 38. Rd7 Bg7 39. Qd3 {1-0 King,D (2514) -Nikolic,P (2659)/
Germany 2000}) 19... Ne8 (19... a5 20. a3) 20. Rad1 Nc4 21. Re2 Rab8 ({on} 
21... f5 $5 {White can sacrifice} 22. Nxf5 gxf5 23. Qxf5 {and there isn't any
forced win but the attack is dangerous} Ng7 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 25. Bc2 Bf6 26. b3
Nb6 27. f4 $40) 22. Ne4 f5 23. Ng5 Bxg5 24. Bxg5 {White has two bishops and a
great control of the center. It doesn't seem easy to take advantage of the
slightly open black king, so Black seems to be slightly better.} Qg7 (24... Qf7
$142 $1 25. Qg3 $140 Rc5) 25. Qg3 h6 26. Bc1 Nf6 27. Bc2 Rc7 28. a4 Rc5 $6 (
28... Rbc8 $142 {with the idea of b4}) 29. axb5 axb5 30. b3 $1 $16 Nb6 31. Ba3
{[%csl Rd6] d6 is hit and Black is forced to sacrifice the exchange.} Rbc8 32.
Bxc5 Rxc5 $16 33. c4 $6 (33. b4 Rc8 34. Qd3 $16 {[%csl Rb5]}) 33... bxc4 34.
bxc4 Nxc4 35. Bb3 Na5 36. Rc2 f4 37. Qf3 e4 38. Qxf4 Nxb3 39. Rxc5 Nxc5 40.
Qxd6 Nfd7 41. Rc1 Qf8 42. Qxg6+ Kh8 43. Ra1 Ne5 44. Qg3 Ncd7 45. Ra6 Kh7 46.
