1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. d4 Bg4 10. d5 Na5 11. Bc2 c6 12. h3 Bc8 {This is the old main line and
also the most popular way for Black to play against the Yates System. The
arising structures are similar to the Najdorf Sicilian.} 13. dxc6 Qc7 14. Nbd2
Qxc6 15. Nf1 Nc4 {Тhis is the main move for Black but there are other moves
as well :} (15... Be6 $5 16. Ng5 (16. Ng3 Rfe8 17. Ng5 ({I would like to show
you another example which can be useful not only for this line but also for
other positions of the same character} 17. Qe2 Rac8 18. Bd3 {leaving the c-
file because Black was threatening ...b5-b4.} Nd7 19. Ng5 Bxg5 20. Bxg5 Nc5 21.
Bc2 {Ovjectively the position is about equal but White has two bishops and
there is everything to play for. I like Kamsky's position here} f6 22. Bc1 Na4
23. Qf3 Rc7 24. Nf5 $14 {the game was eventually drawn Kamsky,G (2735)-Anand,V
(2725) Monte Carlo 1996}) 17... Bd7 18. a4 Nc4 (18... Rec8 $1 {is better when
I think Black is just fine.}) 19. b3 Nb6 20. a5 Nc8 21. Bd2 Bd8 22. Bd3 Ne7 23.
c4 Qb7 24. Nf3 $14 {Gashimov,V (2740)-Roiz,M (2658) Novi Sad 2009}) 16... Bd7
17. a4 {would be my choice. It's hard to see how Black can benefit from not
playing Nc4, meanwhile White keeps his options of Ng3 or Ne3.} Rfc8 18. Ne3 h6
19. Nf3 $1 Be6 (19... Nc4 {this seems critical to me, makes sense to trade a
bad knight for a potentially dangerous one} 20. Nd5 Nxd5 21. exd5 Qc7 22. b3 (
22. Nd4 $5 exd4 23. Qd3 f5 24. Rxe7 Qd8 25. Re2 dxc3 26. Qxc3 {the position is
about equal} Ne5 27. Qg3 Qf6 28. Bf4 Rc5 29. Rae1 bxa4 30. Qa3) 22... Na5 23.
axb5 axb5 24. Bd2 Nb7 25. b4 $13) 20. Nh4 Bf8 21. Nhf5 g6 {and here there is a
nice tactical idea} 22. Ng4 $1 Nxg4 23. hxg4 Kh7 (23... gxf5 24. gxf5 Bc4 25.
Re3 {is winning for White.}) 24. Re3 $18 {White is winning. The rest of the
game is just a beautiful attack in motion} d5 25. Nxh6 d4 26. Rh3 Kg7 27. Nf5+
Kg8 28. Bg5 f6 29. axb5 axb5 30. Bxf6 Bxf5 31. Rxa5 Rxa5 32. Bb3+ Be6 33. Rh8+
Kf7 34. Qf3 Ra1+ 35. Kh2 Ke8 36. Bg5 Kd7 37. Rh7+ Kd6 38. Bxe6 Re8 39. Bd5 Qc8
40. Qf6+ Kc5 41. b4# {1-0 (41) Watson,W (2525)-Littlewood,P (2460) London 1991}
) (15... Re8 16. Ng3 (16. Ne3 {is likely to transpose after} Be6 17. Ng5) 16...
Be6 {see 15...Be6} (16... Bf8 $6 17. Bg5 $1 $14 {is a typical idea})) 16. a4 {
16.Ng3 is another option but I like this move because it activates the rook on
a1 and at the same times puts some pressure on b5. Also, one of White's ideas
is to play b2-b3 and answer Nb6 with a4-a5, thus restricting the knight. In
this file, we focus on the move 16...Be6} Be6 17. Ng5 $1 {This move should be
played immediately. White wants to provoke the weakening h7-h6.} Bd7 18. b3 Na5
19. Bd2 Rfc8 {Let's examine other alternatives} (19... Qc7 20. axb5 axb5 21.
Ne3 Rfc8 22. Qe2 h6 23. Nf3 Be6 24. Reb1 Nb7 25. Nd5 ({Аs a general rule,
when Black goes Nb7, White should play b4 with the idea to restrict the
mobility of the knight.} 25. b4 Qc6 26. Nf5 Bf8 27. Bd3 Bc4 28. Bxc4 bxc4 29.
Ng3 {I prefer White here because the c4-pawn is a long-term weakness.}) 25...
Bxd5 26. exd5 Qc5 27. Rxa8 Rxa8 28. c4 bxc4 29. bxc4 Qc7 {Kleiser,G (2229)
-Tritt,M (2211) ICCF 2009 The position is level}) (19... Bd8 $5 20. Ne3 (20.
Ng3 Re8 {Quillan,G (2339) -Haslinger,S (2511) Liverpool 2008} 21. Nf3 {with
the idea of Nh4 followed by Qf3 and Nhf5.}) 20... h6 21. Nf3 Be6 (21... Bb6 $6
22. Nh4 $1 {is dangerous for black}) 22. b4 Nc4 23. Nxc4 Bxc4 24. Nh4 Be6 (
24... d5 $5 25. Nf5 $1 {is a beautiful idea} Nxe4 (25... dxe4 26. Qc1 $3 {
and white is ready to sacrifice on h6 or on g7. For example:} Rc8 27. axb5 axb5
28. Bxh6 Ne8 29. Bxe4 $16) 26. axb5 Bxb5 (26... axb5 27. Rxa8 Qxa8 28. Bxe4
dxe4 29. Bxh6 {is winning}) 27. c4 $1 Bxc4 28. Bxe4 dxe4 29. Rc1 {with the
strong threat of Qg4} Qf6 30. Nxh6+ gxh6 31. Rxc4 $14 {a very nice example of
how White can develop the initiative in this line.}) 25. Qf3 $14 d5 $6 (25...
Nh7 26. Nf5 Bxf5 27. Qxf5 Bg5 28. Bxg5 Nxg5 29. Ra3 $5 {is pleasant for White.}
) 26. Nf5 dxe4 27. Rxe4 $1 Bxf5 28. Qxf5 Qd6 29. Rd1 $16 g6 30. Qf3 Nxe4 31.
Bxe4 Rc8 32. Bxh6 Qf6 33. Bxf8 Kxf8 34. Bb7 Rb8 35. a5 {White had a clear
advantage in Negi,P (2529) -Batchuluun,C (2415)/Cebu City 2007, even though he
failed to convert it.}) 20. Ne3 (20. Ng3 $5) 20... h6 21. Nf3 Be6 22. Nh4 $1
Bf8 {Necessary against Nhf5} (22... Nxe4 $2 {is a serious mistake} 23. axb5
axb5 24. Bxe4 Qxe4 25. Nef5 Qb7 (25... Bxf5 26. Rxe4 Bxe4 27. Qg4 $16) 26. Qg4
$36 {with a decisive attack}) 23. Nhf5 {Not a bad move but White missed a
clear road to an advantage with a common operation} (23. c4 $1 {[%csl Ya5]
attacking the knight on a5} Nb7 (23... Nxb3 $2 {drastic and insufficient} 24.
Bxb3 Nxe4 25. cxb5 axb5 (25... Bxb3 26. bxc6 Bxd1 27. Rexd1 Rxc6 28. Rab1 $18)
26. Bxe6 fxe6 27. Rc1 Qd7 28. Rxc8 Rxc8 29. axb5 Qxb5 30. Qg4 $18) 24. Nd5 {
[%csl Gd5]} bxc4 $6 (24... Bxd5 25. axb5 $1 {a nice intermediate move} axb5 (
25... Qc7 26. bxa6 $16 (26. b6 $5 $16)) 26. Rxa8 Rxa8 27. cxd5 $18 {[%csl Yb7]
[%cal Yb3b4] followed by b3-b4 and White has a huge positional advantage.}) 25.
Nxf6+ gxf6 26. Re3 $1 $18 {with a winning attack against the black king}) 23...
Qb6 (23... Nxe4 {Black runs into trouble after} 24. Qg4 Nf6 (24... Nxd2 25.
Nxh6+ Kh8 26. Nxf7+ Kg8 (26... Bxf7 27. Qh4+ Kg8 28. Qh7#) 27. Qh5 e4 28. Ng5
Bf5 29. Nxf5 $18) 25. Nxh6+ Kh8 26. Qh4 $18) 24. Nd5 {Jakovenko has managed to
achieve a clear domination in the center.} (24. b4 $5 {is also a reasonable
alternative} Nc4 (24... Nc6 25. Qf3 $16) 25. Nxc4 Bxc4 26. Qf3 $14 {with an
initiative.}) 24... Qd8 (24... Nxd5 {is strongly met with} 25. Nxh6+ $3 (25.
exd5 Bxf5 26. Bxf5 $14) 25... gxh6 26. exd5 Bd7 27. Qh5 $18 {followed by
Re3-Rg3 and Black can resign.}) 25. Qf3 $1 (25. c4 $5 Nb7 26. axb5 axb5 27.
Rxa8 Rxa8 28. cxb5 $14) 25... Nxd5 {Black is far from equalizing here. For
instance:} (25... Bxf5 26. exf5 Nxd5 27. Qxd5 b4 28. c4 Nc6 29. Be3 $16 {
[%csl Yd4]}) (25... Bxd5 26. exd5 Rc5 27. Ne3 $16) 26. exd5 (26. Nxh6+ gxh6 27.
exd5 Bd7 28. Qh5 f5) 26... Bxf5 27. Qxf5 (27. Bxf5 {allows} Nxb3 $1 {with a
counterplay.}) 27... g6 28. Qg4 (28. Qd3 $1 {[%csl Yb5] was better since Black
would have less counterplay than in the game.} bxa4 (28... Rcb8 $6 29. axb5
axb5 30. Ra3 $16) 29. Rxa4 Nb7 30. Qg3 Bg7 31. Rb4 Rab8 32. c4 a5 (32... Nc5
33. Rxb8 Rxb8 34. b4 $16 {[%cal Yg3a3]}) 33. Ra4 Ra8 34. Qe3 Nc5 35. Ra3 $14)
28... b4 $5 {A nice try for a counterplay. Black sacrifices a pawn and in
return the white queen will be left out of play on a3.} 29. Qxb4 Rab8 30. Qa3
$8 f5 (30... h5 31. Rab1 $18) 31. c4 e4 32. Rab1 h5 33. Bc3 Nb7 34. a5 $6 (34.
Qb2 a5 35. f3 exf3 36. Bf6 Qb6+ 37. Bd4 Nc5 $2 38. Re6 $18 Kh7 39. Bxf5 gxf5
40. Qc2 {White wins.}) 34... Bg7 35. Bd2 (35. Qa1 Qd7) 35... Bd4 $44 36. Kf1
Qf6 37. Qc1 Nd8 38. Bg5 Qe5 39. Bf4 Qf6 {The position is not that clear
anymore but Jakovenko continues playing for a win} 40. f3 $1 Nf7 41. fxe4 g5 (
41... fxe4 42. Ke2) 42. e5 $6 (42. Be3 Bxe3 43. Qxe3 f4 $13 44. e5 $1 Nxe5 45.
Qa7 $16) 42... Bxe5 43. Bd2 g4 $40 {Now Black has some serious initiative.} 44.
Kg1 (44. Bf4 gxh3 45. gxh3 Qh4) 44... gxh3 45. Qd1 (45. Re2 {was the only move}
Qh4 46. Qf1 $11) 45... Qh4 $19 {the rest of the game is pretty simple} 46. Qf3
hxg2 47. Kxg2 (47. Qxg2+ Kh8 $19) (47. Qxf5 Qh2+ 48. Kf2 g1=Q+) (47. Rxe5 Nxe5
48. Qxf5 Qh1+ 49. Kf2 Rf8 $19) 47... Qh2+ 48. Kf1 Qxd2 49. Re2 Qh6 50. Rg2+ Kh8
51. Qxf5 Rg8 52. Rg6 Rxg6 53. Qxg6 Bc3 54. Qxh6+ Nxh6 55. Kg2 Re8 56. Kf3 Ng4
57. Rh1 Re3+ 58. Kf4 Re5 59. Bd1 Nf6 60. Rg1 Bd2+ 61. Kf3 Re3+ 62. Kg2 Re1 63.
Rxe1 Bxe1 64. Kf3 Bxa5 65. Kf4 Kg7 {0-1 (65) Jakovenko,D (2708) -Marin,M (2533)
Torrelavega 2007} *

