1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. d4 Bg4 10. d5 Na5 11. Bc2 c6 12. h3 Bc8 13. dxc6 Qc7 14. Nbd2 Qxc6 15.
Nf1 Nc4 16. a4 {This is the point where Black has several choices and
different plans. In the previous file, we analyzed the move 16...Be6. Now, we
shall have a look at the flexible 16...Re8.} Re8 $5 17. Ng3 Be6 {Developing in
Sicilian style. Black's piece coordination looks excellent and it is
everything he would like to achieve in the Sicilian Najdorf variation.} (17...
Bf8 18. b3 {White has a few alternatives here that I would like to mention:} (
18. Qe2 $5 {is quite flexible and would be my choice. In this position, our
strategy would totally depend on how Black reacts.} Be6 (18... Bb7 19. Bg5) 19.
Ng5) ({Perhaps the most direct line is} 18. axb5 $5 axb5 19. Rxa8 Qxa8 20. b3
Nb6 21. Be3 Qc6 22. Bd3 {when Black's queenside is vulnerable.}) 18... Nb6 (
18... Na5 $6 19. Bg5 $1 {taking advantage of the move Bf8} Be7 20. Nh4 $14 (20.
axb5 axb5 21. Ra2 Be6 22. Nf5 {looks promising as well.})) 19. Bg5 Nbd7 20.
axb5 (20. Bd3 Bb7 21. c4 $5 {could lead to an interesting play but Black has
enough resources.} bxc4 22. Bxc4 h6 23. Rc1 Qb6 24. Be3 Qd8 {The problem now
is that the e4-pawn is under attack and Black will carry out the d6-d5 break
under favourable circumstances. For example:} 25. Nd2 d5 26. exd5 Nxd5 27. Nde4
N7b6 $1 28. Bc5 Nxc4 29. bxc4 Nf4 30. Bxf8 Qxd1 31. Rcxd1 Rxf8 {is completely
satisfactory for Black.}) 20... axb5 21. Rxa8 Qxa8 22. Bd3 {[%csl Rb5]} Qb8 $6
(22... Qc6 {was necessary in order to keep the equality. Black not only
defends b5 but also attacks c3.} 23. Qe2 Ba6 24. Ra1 h6 25. Be3 {with chances
for both sides}) 23. Qe2 $14 (23. b4 {may be even better. For instance:} h6 24.
Bd2 Ba6 25. Nh2 $1 {As the reader should have seen by now, this is a typical
attacking regroupment. In the future, White can follow with 26.Ng4 followed by
Qf3 and Nf5.}) 23... Ba6 24. Ra1 Qb6 $6 (24... Qb7 $16) 25. b4 $1 Rc8 26. Bd2
Nb8 (26... Qc6 $142 27. Ra5 Rb8 28. Be1 $16 {with the idea of Qa2 looks strong.
}) 27. Ra5 Nc6 28. Be3 Qb7 29. Bxb5 Bxb5 30. Rxb5 Qa8 31. Kh2 $16 {and White
went on to win in Tseshkovsky,V (2528)-Stambulian,A (2396) Krasnodar 2001.}) (
17... Bb7 18. Qe2 Bf8 (18... d5 $5 19. exd5 (19. axb5 axb5 20. Rxa8 Bxa8 21.
exd5 Qxd5 (21... Nxd5 22. b3 Nd6 23. Nxe5 Qxc3 24. Bb2 $14) 22. Bg5 (22. Nf5
$142 Bf8 23. b3 Nd6 24. Nxd6 Bxd6 25. Bg5 $14 {and White is slightly better
since Black cannot prevent the doubled pawns on f6.}) 22... h6 23. Bxf6 Bxf6
24. Be4 (24. Rd1 Qe6 25. Bf5 Qb6 26. Ne4 $5 {was another way to coordinate the
pieces}) 24... Qe6 25. Bxa8 Rxa8 {Sutovsky,E (2590) -Garcia,G (2480)/Groningen
1997} 26. Ne4 $11) 19... Nxd5 (19... Qxd5 $5 {we should react with} 20. b3 $1
e4 (20... Nb6 21. axb5 axb5 22. Rxa8 Rxa8 (22... Bxa8 23. Qxe5 $16) 23. Qxe5
$16) (20... Na5 21. axb5 axb5 22. Qxe5 Bd6 23. Qxd5 Rxe1+ 24. Nxe1 Nxd5 25. Ne4
Be5 26. Nd3 $14) 21. Nxe4 Nd6 22. Nxd6 Bxd6 23. Be3 $14 {I believe that Black
does have some compensation here but nothing great. He will have to fight hard
to equalize}) 20. b3 Nd6 21. axb5 axb5 22. Rxa8 Bxa8 23. Nxe5 Qxc3 24. Bb2 $14)
19. Bg5 $1 ({White must be careful here not to play} 19. Bd3 d5 $1 $11) 19...
Nd7 (19... d5 $2 20. Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 (20... gxf6 21. Nh5 $16) 21. exd5 $16 {
now if black plays} Bxd5 22. axb5 axb5 23. Qd3 e4 24. Nxe4 Rxe4 25. Qxd5 $16) (
{Taking on b2 is a mistake} 19... Nxb2 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Nh5 Re6 22. Bb3 $16 {
White has a huge advantage.}) 20. b3 Ncb6 21. a5 Nc8 {and now White can obtain
a slight advantage with the move} 22. b4 $5 {.For example:} (22. Bd2 {
Fressinet,L (2640) -Shchekachev,A (2561) Paris 2006}) 22... Ne7 (22... Qxc3 $6
{is critical but after} 23. Rab1 $1 $44 {White has a big compensation for the
pawn.}) (22... h6 23. Bb3 $1 {[%csl Yf7]}) 23. Bb3 h6 (23... Qxc3 {is worse
now because of.} 24. Qa2 $18) 24. Bxe7 Rxe7 25. Nf5 $16 {and Black must play
Re6 because after} Ree8 26. Qa2 {White is already winning.}) (17... g6 {
is rarely played but it's not bad at all!} 18. b3 Nb6 19. a5 Nbd7 20. Bd2 {
looks like the most logical continuation} Bb7 (20... Nf8 21. b4 Be6 22. Rc1
Rac8 23. Bb1 {with the idea of Bg5 next followed by Nf1. Nevertheless, it
should be equal with best play from Black. For example:} N8d7 $1 24. Bg5 d5 25.
Bxf6 Bxf6 26. exd5 Bxd5 27. Be4 Bxe4 28. Nxe4 Be7 29. Qb3 Qc4 30. Qxc4 Rxc4 31.
Rcd1 Rc7 32. g4 f6 33. Rd5 Nf8 34. Red1 Ne6 $11) 21. b4 d5 {Not always this
rupture works out well for Black.} 22. exd5 Nxd5 23. Bb3 Rad8 24. Qc2 Kg7 (
24... Kh8 25. Rad1) 25. Rad1 Nc7 26. h4 f6 27. h5 {White's attack is already
decisive.} Nf8 {King,D (2495)-Van der Wiel,J (2545) Palma de Mallorca 1989}) (
17... h6 {As usual, whenever Black plays h6, White should attack by playing}
18. Nh4 $1 Bb7 $2 (18... Be6 {is better although White keeps the initiative
with} 19. Qf3 Nh7 20. Nhf5) 19. Nhf5 d5 $2 20. Qf3 $1 Bf8 (20... dxe4 21. Nxe4
{would be terrible for Black. Qg3 is coming on the next move.}) 21. exd5 Qxd5
22. Ne4 $16 {White has a clear advantage.} Re6 {Oparin,G (2542)-Stukopin,A 
(2553) Loo RUS 2014 and here} 23. axb5 axb5 24. Rxa8 Bxa8 25. b3 Nb6 26. Qg3
Nh5 27. Qg4 g6 28. Bxh6 {was decisive.}) 18. Ng5 $1 {We must immediately
disturb Back's ideal development, just like in the game Jakovenko - Marin.} Bd7
19. b3 Na5 (19... Nb6 20. a5 Nc8 21. Bd2 h6 22. Nf3 $14) 20. Bd2 {Typical move
in this system. White creates the threat of c3-c4 at some point.} Bd8 $1 {
I believe that this is Black's best option here but the alternatives are also
playable and lead to complex play.} (20... Qc7 21. axb5 axb5 22. Qe2 h6 23. Nf3
Bf8 (23... Be6 24. Reb1 {simply defending b3. White is now prepared to seize
the control of the light squares.} Reb8 25. Nh2 (25. Nh4 $5) 25... Qb7 26. Ng4
(26. Nhf1 {or the immediate jump to f5 look like interesting options}) (26. Nf5
) 26... Nc6 (26... Nxg4 27. hxg4 b4 28. Nf5 $1 {is unclear and I think Black
should be okay but the position just looks easier to play for White.}) 27. b4
$1 Nxg4 28. hxg4 Rxa1 29. Rxa1 Qc8 30. Bd1 $1 {Since Nxb4 was a threat} d5 $2 {
too early.} (30... Bf8 $14 {with a slightly passive but solid position was
needed}) 31. exd5 Bxd5 {We have been following the game Becerra Rivero,J (2556)
-Kamsky,G (2686)/ San Diego 2006 played at the US Championship. Now White
could have secured a clear advantage with the strong} 32. Bc2 $1 $16 {At this
point, Nxb4 does not work anymore because of Bf5. Also, the move Qd3 is coming
next.}) 24. Ra2 $5 {With this move, White is planning to double the rooks
along the a-file. In this way, he forces the black knight into the unfavorable
b7-square. Once, the knight lands on b7, White can restrict it by means of
b3-b4.} (24. Nh2 $5) (24. Nh4 $5) 24... Nb7 25. Rxa8 Rxa8 26. b4 {As we
pointed out on a number of occasions, this is a standard positional idea by
means of which White is keeping the knight away from c5.} Re8 $2 (26... Nd8 $1
{was needed} 27. Bb3 $13) 27. Bb3 Bc6 28. Nh2 $1 {This idea now is quite
strong because white will eliminate a key defender of the d5-square and the
black king.} (28. c4 $5) 28... Qd7 29. Ng4 Nxg4 30. hxg4 d5 {In many lines,
Black achieves this freeing rupture but it is not clear at all that it
improves his position. In fact, in many cases, it just makes it worse.} 31. Rd1
(31. Bxh6 $1 {was a very strong tactic here} dxe4 (31... gxh6 32. exd5 Bxd5 33.
Rd1 {wins}) 32. Be3 $16) 31... d4 32. cxd4 Qxd4 33. Qf3 $18 Nd6 34. Bxh6 Qa7
35. Bxg7 {1-0 Svidler,P (2640) -Stefansson,H (2555)/Torshavn 1997 A very nice
game by Svidler!}) 21. Nh5 $146 {This was a new idea at the time when Michael
Adams played it.} (21. Qe2 $5 h6 22. Nf3 Bb6 23. axb5 axb5 24. Nh4 Be6 25. Reb1
) 21... h6 22. Nxf6+ Bxf6 23. Nf3 Qc7 24. axb5 axb5 25. Bd3 Be6 26. Ra3 Qb7 $6
(26... Rec8 {looks like a better try. The position is balanced.}) 27. Nh2 $1
Bg5 (27... Be7 {trying to attack the white rook on a3 doesn't work} 28. Ng4 d5
29. Ra1 $1 $36 {and again, we can see how the d5-push has only helped White.})
28. Bxg5 hxg5 29. b4 $1 Nc4 (29... Nc6 30. Rxa8 Rxa8 31. Be2 $1 {[%csl Yd6]
[%cal Yd1d6]} (31. Nf1 Ne7) 31... Qb8 32. Ng4 Ra2 33. Ne3 $14) 30. Rxa8 Qxa8
31. Bxc4 Bxc4 32. Qxd6 $16 Qd8 33. Rd1 (33. Qxd8 Rxd8 34. Ng4 f6 35. Ne3 $16)
33... Qxd6 34. Rxd6 Ra8 35. Ng4 f6 36. Ne3 Ra3 37. Nd5 Ra1+ 38. Kh2 Ra2 39. Kg3
Rc2 40. Rd7 Bxd5 41. Rxd5 Rxc3+ 42. f3 Rb3 43. Rxb5 Kf7 44. Rb7+ Ke6 45. b5 Rb2
46. b6 Kd6 47. Rb8 $2 (47. Kg4 Rxg2+ 48. Kf5 Rf2 49. Rxg7 Rxf3+ 50. Kg6 Rxh3
51. b7 Rb3 52. Kxf6 g4 53. Kf5 g3 54. Rxg3 Rxb7 55. Rg6+ Kc5 56. Kxe5 {with a
winning position because the black king is too far and cut}) 47... Kc6 48. Rg8
Rxb6 49. Rxg7 Kd6 50. Kg4 Rb2 51. Kf5 (51. g3) 51... Rxg2 52. Rf7 Rg3 53. Rxf6+
Ke7 54. Re6+ Kf7 55. Rxe5 Rxf3+ 56. Kg4 Re3 57. Rf5+ Ke6 58. Rxg5 {Adams,M 
