1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. d4 Bg4 10. d5 Na5 11. Bc2 c6 12. h3 Bc8 13. dxc6 Qc7 14. Nbd2 Qxc6 15.
Nf1 Nc4 16. a4 {After having already examined the moves 16...Be6 and 16...Rfe8,
in this chapter we will analyze the moves 16...Bb7 and 16...g6 which was
played by the legendary Henrique Mecking.} g6 (16... Bb7 {is another serious
alternative} 17. Ng3 {It makes sense to attack the f5-square immediately but
white should look into the alternatives here.} (17. Ne3 $5 Nxe3 18. Bxe3 Rfe8
19. Bg5 h6 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Bb3 {This position is slightly better for White
since the d5-square is weak and the pressure along the long diagonal is
annoying.}) (17. Ra2 $5 Nb6 $6 18. Bg5 h6 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. a5 Nd7 21. Ne3 $14
{In the future, the weakness of the d5-square and the d6-pawn will tell. Black
has difficulties to create counterplay in this position.}) 17... g6 18. Bd3 (
18. Qe2 {as played by Sutovsky is another possibility. The general idea is to
put pressure on b5} Rfc8 19. axb5 axb5 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. Bd3 $14 {and
according to Sutovsky's analysis, White is slightly better. Sutovsky,E (2590)
-Gabriel,C (2575)/Bad Homburg 1997}) 18... Rfc8 (18... Nb6 19. Bh6 (19. a5 Nbd7
) (19. axb5 axb5 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. Bg5 Nc4 22. Qc1 $11) 19... Rfd8 $2 ({
Here, Black misses an important and instructive sacrifice} 19... Nxa4 $1 20.
Bxf8 Bxf8 {with a full compensation for the exchange. It is extremely
difficult for White to create any active play. Meanwhile, the knight is
returning back to c5 on the next move.}) 20. axb5 axb5 21. Qe2 $16 {Black has
serious problems now.} b4 (21... Nc4 $2 22. b3) 22. cxb4 Rxa1 23. Rxa1 d5 24.
Nxe5 Qd6 25. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 26. e5 Qxb4 27. exf6 Bxf6 28. Bd2 Qd6 29. Qf3 Kg7 30.
Nh5+ gxh5 31. Qxh5 Kf8 32. Bh6+ Ke7 33. Re1+ Kd7 34. Qf5+ {1-0 Yudasin,L (2610)
-Tatai,S (2385)/Reggio Emilia 1998 A nice game by Yudasin}) 19. Qe2 bxa4 20.
Bg5 Nb6 (20... a3 $5 {breaking the pawn structure on the queenside is tempting}
21. bxa3 Rab8 22. Nh4 $1 Na5 (22... Bd8 $142 23. Nhf5 gxf5 24. Nxf5 d5 {
only move. White was simply threatening Qf3 with a strong attack.} 25. Bxc4
dxc4 26. Qf3 Kh8 27. Nh6 Nxe4 28. Nxf7+ Kg7 {only move} 29. Bxd8 Rxd8 30. Nxd8
Rxd8 31. Rab1 {White's position is easier because of the vulnerable black king.
}) 23. Nhf5 Bd8 24. Nh6+ $14 {Black's position looks a bit dangerous here. I
believe that Black should be fine but his play is far from obvious.}) 21. Nh4
Kf8 22. Nhf5 $3 {Negi goes for a thematic sacrifice which will yield a
long-term initiative.} (22. Qf3 $14) 22... gxf5 23. Nxf5 Bd8 $2 (23... Rc7 {
was the only move} 24. Qe3 Ke8 25. Qg3 Nbd7 26. Qh4 Qb6 27. Rxa4 {Black still
has big problems to solve. Although he does not face a direct threats, he
doesn't have active options. Furthermore, Re3 is coming.}) 24. Qf3 $1 $18 {
the sacrifice paid off quickly} Nbd7 25. Bc2 Nc5 26. Bh6+ $18 (26. Qg3 {
with threats like Qh4, Red1 should win easily} Ne6 $2 27. Bxa4 {and Bh6+!})
26... Ke8 27. Rad1 $6 {this wasn't the best although it was good enough} (27.
Ng7+ Kd7 28. Bg5 {was simple and strong}) 27... Be7 28. Bg5 Ncd7 29. Qg3 (29.
Re3 $1 $16) 29... a3 30. Bh4 Bf8 31. bxa3 Qxc3 $17 {the game is now very
unclear but still white won after Stefansson made maistakes. Negi,P (2514)
-Stefansson,H (2583) Differdange LUX 2008}) (16... h6 17. Ng3 Re8 18. Nh4 $14)
17. Qe2 {Vallejo follows the typical ideas of this line. It is worth noting
that since black has played g7-g6 so early, White doesn't hurry with Ng3 and
keeps the knight on f1 until a better moment to improve it comes.} Bd7 18. Bd3
Nh5 19. Bh6 Rfc8 (19... Nf4 20. Bxf4 exf4 21. e5 $14) 20. b3 $1 Na5 21. axb5
axb5 22. Ne3 $1 {White goes for the weak d5-square.} Nf6 (22... Nxb3 23. Nd5
Bd8 24. Rab1 Ra3 25. Qd1 Nc5 26. Bxb5 {White gets his pawn back with a firm
control of the light squares.}) 23. b4 {With the c4-square under control,
White forces the black knight to retreat to b7.} Nb7 24. Rxa8 Rxa8 25. Bg5 $1 {
fighting for an exclusive control of the d5-square.} Be6 (25... Qxc3 $4 26.
Bxf6 Bxf6 27. Nd5 $18) 26. Rc1 Ra2 $2 {This active move that seems to solve
Black's problems is a blunder thatWhite doesn't miss.} ({better was} 26... Nd8
27. Bxb5 Qxe4 28. Rd1 $14) 27. Nd5 $1 {A nice shot attacking the bishop on e7
and interrupting the defense of the a2-rook.} Bxd5 {Only move} (27... Rxe2 $2
28. Nxe7+ Kg7 29. Nxc6 $18) 28. exd5 Qa6 (28... Qxd5 {Now white can win with}
29. c4 $1 Rxe2 30. cxd5 Rb2 31. Rc7 $18) 29. Bxb5 $18 {Black does not have any
compensation for the material loss} Qa7 30. Qe1 Bd8 31. Bc4 Ra3 32. Nd2 Kg7 33.
Qe3 Bb6 34. Bh6+ Kh8 35. Qf3 Ng8 36. Bg5 Kg7 37. g4 h6 38. Bh4 Ra1 39. Rxa1
Qxa1+ 40. Kg2 g5 41. Bg3 Nf6 42. h4 Qc1 43. Ne4 $5 Nxe4 44. Qxe4 Qxc3 45. Bd3 {
[%csl Gd3,Ge4][%cal Re4h7]} Kf8 46. Qh7 Ke7 47. Bf5 {[%csl Rf7,Rh6][%cal Rf5e6]
} Qxb4 48. Qxh6 Qd2 49. hxg5 Qxd5+ 50. Kh2 Bxf2 (50... Nd8 51. g6 $1 fxg6 52.
Qg7+ Qf7 53. Bh4+ $18) (50... Bc5 51. Qf6+ Kf8 52. Qh8+ Ke7 53. g6 $18) 51.
Bxf2 Nc5 52. g6 Qa2 53. Qh4+ Kf8 54. Qh8+ Ke7 55. Kg1 fxg6 56. Bh4+ {1-0 (56)
