1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O {
This is the move order some players use when they want to play the Marshall
Attack. I would like to share some possible solutions for White based on the
move 8.a4 known as the Anti-Marshall.} 8. a4 {Here, Black has three main
replies which are 8...Bb7, 8...Rb8, and 8...b4 which considered to be the main
response. All these three moves have pros and cons and they are different in
the small details that I'll try to explain here:} b4 (8... Rb8 {has the
drawback of surrendering the a-file too early. Therefore, White can continue
now with} 9. axb5 axb5 {and now he can follow with either 10.c3 followed by
d2-d4 or 10.d3 with more restricted play.} 10. d3) (8... Bb7 {The problem with
this move is that the bishop will not be able to oppose to White's b3 bishop
and the f5-square is now left unprotected. I like the development with 9.d3
followed by 10.Nbd2 keeping the bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal.}) (8... Na5 {
is an interesting line to force the gambit but should still be dubious} 9. Ba2
d5 10. exd5 e4 11. Ne5 Bb7 (11... Nxd5 12. Nc3 $1 {White is just ahead in
development.} Nb4 (12... Nxc3 13. dxc3 $16) 13. Bxf7+ $1 Rxf7 14. Nxf7 Kxf7 15.
axb5 axb5 16. Nxe4 Kg8 17. d4 Bf5 18. c3 Nd5 19. Qf3 Be6 20. Bg5 {White has a
decisive advantage. Zenker,O (2173)-Leonard,M (2040) LSS email 2007}) 12. Nc3
Bd6 {is also interesting here and now} (12... b4 13. Nxe4 b3 14. cxb3 Nxe4 15.
Rxe4 Qxd5 16. d3 Bb4 17. Nf3 c5 18. Bd2 Nc6 19. Bc3 Rad8 20. Qf1 a5 {Roganovic,
M (2474)-Brenjo,S (2495) Kragujevac 2009} 21. Rae1 $14) 13. d4 exd3 14. Nxd3 b4
15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Rxe4 b3 17. Bxb3 Nxb3 18. cxb3 Bxd5 19. Rd4 c6 20. Nf4 $14) (
8... d5 $6 {Again, this gambit seems interesting but insufficient. I choose
the most practical way:} 9. axb5 dxe4 10. bxc6 exf3 11. Qxf3 e4 12. Qe2 $146
Bd6 (12... Bg4 13. Qe3 $14 {the bishop on g4 gets in the way of his own pieces}
) 13. h3 Qe8 14. d4 exd3 15. Qxe8 Rxe8 16. Rxe8+ Nxe8 17. cxd3 $14 {there are
no signs of an attack and all that's left is an endgame in which Black will
have to fight hard to achieve a draw.}) 9. a5 $5 {Although this move does not
promise an advantage, it seems to me that White obtains an easy and harmonius
play.} *

