1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. a4
Rb8 {This is not played very often at GM level and it's not without a reason.
After all, Black simply gets a worse version of the main Ruy Lopez having a
rook on b8 and the a-file being already under White's control. The Spanish
Grandmaster Ivan Salgado has a couple of interesting games against this move.}
9. axb5 axb5 10. c3 {This move order allows black to play the Marshall Attack
even in a slightly worse version with the rook on b8 and the A file open, even
so it is quite playable for black.} (10. h3 {could be an interesting move order
}) 10... d6 (10... d5 {in Marshall style is again possible.} 11. exd5 Nxd5 (
11... e4 12. dxc6 exf3 13. g3 $1 $16) 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Rxe5 {In this position,
we have the two main Marshall ideas - 13...Nf6 and 13...c6.} Nf6 (13... Bb7 14.
d4 Bf6 15. Re1 Re8 16. Bd2 Qd7 17. Na3 Rxe1+ 18. Qxe1 Be7 19. Qe2 Bc6 20. Nc2
$16 {Palac,M (2545)-Stevic,H (2395) Makarska 1996}) (13... c6 {this is
identical to the Marshall main line. In this case, however, White enjoys the
open a-file since black has played Rb8. This detail makes the whole difference.
} 14. d4 Bd6 15. Re1 Qh4 16. g3 Qh3 17. Qd3 Bf5 18. Qf1 Qh5 {If there were
pawns on a2 and a6, we would have gotten the main line in Marshall. In that
case, the black rook would have been on b8. Black has compensation for the
pawn but I believe that White can slowly finish his development, even if it's
not too pretty at first sight.} 19. Nd2 $146 (19. Be3 {has been played with
the same idea but perhaps} b4 {gives Black too much counterplay.}) 19... Rbe8
20. Bd1 Qg6 21. Nf3 Bd3 22. Qg2 {the plan is to follow with Bd2.} Be4 ({
I was worried about} 22... Bc2 23. Bxc2 Qxc2 24. Qf1 h6 25. Rxe8 Rxe8 26. Ne1
Qe4 27. Bd2 {and White is getting his pieces out.}) 23. Bd2 Qf6 {and now comes
an interesting idea} 24. Rxe4 $1 Rxe4 25. Ra6 Rc8 26. Ne5 Rxe5 27. dxe5 Bxe5
28. Bb3 {White must be clearly better.}) 14. d4 Bd6 15. Re2 $1 {and now let's
have a look at some attacking moves for Black} (15. Re1 $6 Ng4 16. h3 Nxf2 {
is a problem}) 15... c5 $5 {Wolff,P (2590)-Fang,J (2400) New York 1994} (15...
Ng4 $6 16. h3 Qh4 17. Nd2 $16 Nxf2 $2 18. Rxf2 Bh2+ 19. Kxh2 Qxf2 20. Qf3 $18 {
Martin Rueda,D (2223)-De la Paz Perdomo,F (2436) Collado Villalba 2002}) (15...
Nh5 16. Nd2 Nf4 17. Re3 $5 $146 Qg5 18. g3 Nh3+ 19. Kf1 Bg4 20. Qe1 Nf4 21. Kg1
Qg6 (21... Nh3+ 22. Kh1) 22. Ne4 Nh3+ 23. Kf1 Qh5 24. Kg2 Ng5 {otherwise f2-f3
comes.} 25. Nxg5 Qxg5 26. Bc2 Qh5 27. h4 {and it seems that White has defended
the kingside.}) 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Qxd8 Rxd8 18. Bf4 Bg4 (18... Rb7 19. Nd2 $16)
19. Rd2 Ne4 20. Bxb8 Nxd2 21. Nxd2 Rxb8 $1 (21... Rxd2 22. Bf4 $1 Rd8 (22...
Rxb2 $4 23. Ra8+ Bf8 24. h3 $1 $18 {nice trick}) 23. Bg5 Re8 24. Be3 $1 Bxe3
25. fxe3 $16) 22. h3 Bd7 23. Nf3 {White is better but black's drawing chances
are real.}) 11. h3 {It's also possible for White to play the direct d2-d4.} (
11. d4 exd4 12. cxd4 d5 (12... Bg4 13. Nc3 $1 {with a slight advantage. Double
pawns don't matter so much here} Bxf3 14. gxf3 $14) 13. e5 Ne4 14. Nc3 Nxc3 15.
bxc3 Be6 {Salgado Lopez,I (2612)-Mariotti,S (2295) Condino 2014} 16. Qd3 $14 {
with the idea of Bc2 - Bh6 or even h2-h4 next.}) 11... Nd7 (11... Be6 {White
has a pleasant choice between} 12. d4 ({or} 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. d3 {with the
plan of Be3-Nbd2. In such structures, White has a slight advantage.}) 12...
Bxb3 13. Qxb3 exd4 14. cxd4 d5 15. e5 Ne4 16. Nbd2 Nxd2 17. Bxd2 Rb6 18. Rec1
Qd7 19. Rc2 f6 20. Rac1 $16 {Gomez Esteban,J (2485) -Sanz Alonso,F (2420)
Canete 1994}) (11... b4 $5 12. d3 Bd7 (12... d5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15.
Rxe5 Be6 {Jakovenko,D (2644)-Khalifman,A (2653) Moscow 2005} 16. c4 $1 Nb6 17.
Bc2 c5 18. Nd2 Nd7 19. Re1 {Although Black must have compensation here,
White's position looks slightly better with Ne4 and Be3 coming next.} Bf6 20.
Ne4 Bd4 21. Qf3 $5) 13. d4 (13. Be3 Ra8 14. Nbd2 {is another quiet way of
playing}) 13... Ra8 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bh4 Rd8 17. Nbd2 Be8 18. Qc2
bxc3 19. bxc3 g5 20. Bg3 $14 {Fedorov,V (2445)-Onischuk,A (2535) Germany 1994})
(11... Bb7 {Black prepares to put pressure on e4 but the bishop on this
diagonal doesn't cover the f5-square. I would seriously consider switching to
the more restricted plan with} 12. d3 Ra8 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. Nbd2 Na5 15. Bc2 c5
16. Nf1 Re8 17. Ng3 g6 18. Bh6 {with a standard Ruy Lopez play.}) 12. d4 Bf6
13. Be3 Ne7 14. Nbd2 c5 15. Nf1 Bb7 16. Ng3 {Both sides follow the standard
play of the Ruy Lopez. White keeps the tension and improves the pieces, until
he finds the right moment to modify the pawn structure.} c4 17. Bc2 g6 18. dxe5
{perhaps a little bit early.} (18. Qd2 {and eventually b2-b3 could be better.})
18... dxe5 19. Qd6 $6 Nc8 (19... Nd5 $1 20. Nf5 {only move} (20. exd5 Be7 21.
Bb6 Bxd6 22. Bxd8 Rfxd8 $17) 20... Nxe3 21. Nxe3 Be7 22. Qd1 $11) 20. Qd2 Qe7 {
Black has equalized. This was a blitz game but I think that the ideas of the
opening and the problems Black experiences here are clear by now. The rest of
the game is rather irrelevant to our subject.} 21. Nh2 h5 22. Bd1 Rd8 23. Bxh5
gxh5 24. Nf5 Qe6 25. Qe2 Bxe4 26. Nh6+ Kh7 27. Qxh5 Bg6 28. Qf3 Ne7 29. Ra7 e4
30. Qg3 Nf5 31. Nxf5 Bxf5 32. Ng4 Bxg4 33. hxg4 Ra8 34. g5 Bg7 35. Rb7 Rdb8 36.
Rc7 Nf8 37. Bc5 Ng6 38. Ba3 Be5 39. Qe3 Bxc7 {0-1 (39) Salgado Lopez,I (2622)
-Bartel,M (2641) Dubai 2014} *

