1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. a4
Bb7 9. d3 {Let's have a look now at some key points of this variation. One of
the main questions here is Can Black play d7-d5? The answer is Yes. It's a
serious option that hasn't been tried too often but it was tried by Magnus
Carlsen, so it should be taken seriously.} d6 (9... d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nbd2 {
White could also take the pawn on e5} (11. axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8 Bxa8 13. Nxe5 Nd4
14. Nd2 Bd6 15. c3 Nxb3 16. Nxb3 c5 17. d4 c4 18. Nc5 b4 $2 {this is a mistake}
(18... Re8 $1 19. Nf3 Nc7 {with a compensation for the pawn but no more.}) 19.
Bd2 bxc3 20. bxc3 Bxc5 21. dxc5 Qc8 22. Qe2 Ne7 (22... Qxc5 23. Nd7 $18) 23.
Be3 Nd5 24. Qxc4 Qf5 25. Bd4 {and White went on to win Ivanchuk,V (2729)
-Bacrot,E (2709) Odessa UKR 2007.}) 11... f6 12. c3 (12. Nf1 {can be
considered and could be an interesting novelty}) 12... Kh8 13. axb5 axb5 14.
Rxa8 Bxa8 15. Ne4 {The position tends to be balanced but White has some play
around the central squares and Black must definitely stay on alert.} b4 (15...
Na5 16. Bc2 c5 17. Ng3 g6 18. h4 $5 {is an example of how White can start
attacking Black's position.}) 16. d4 {This leads to massive exchanges} (16. Bd2
$5 {is a reasonable option}) 16... bxc3 17. bxc3 exd4 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. cxd4
Bb4 20. Bd2 $11 {Caruana,F (2808)-Carlsen,M (2832) Stavanger NOR 2017}) (9...
Re8 {is flexible and keeps Black able to choose between d7-d6 and d7-d5. Later,
he can even play sometimes Bc5.} 10. Nbd2 {was Kasparov's choice as well as
Anand's one.} (10. Bg5 {is an interesting try for Black when he does not want
to risk much. A recent game saw} d6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Bd5 Qc8 13. c3 Nd8 14.
Bxb7 Qxb7 15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Qxa8 17. Na3 c6 18. Nc2 Ne6 19. Nb4 Qb7 20. g3
$14 {Vasquez Schroeder,R (2555)-Fressinet,L (2667) Barcelona ESP 2017 In such
kind of positions, White's knights are to be preferred. White's advantage is
not big but he can play for a win without any risk.}) 10... Bf8 11. c3 Na5 (
11... h6 12. Ba2 $1 {with ideas like b2-b4 or axb5 and Qb3.} b4 (12... d6 13.
Nh4 $1 {Here we can see the problems of having developed the bishop to b7.} (
13. axb5 axb5 14. Qb3 Qd7 15. Qxb5 Reb8 16. Qb3 Ra7 17. Qc2 Rba8 18. b4 Ba6 {
Jakovenko,D (2644)-Tomashevsky,E (2564) Moscow 2005} 19. Rb1 $5 Bxd3 20. Bxf7+
Qxf7 21. Qxd3 {White is a pawn up while the compensation is rather unclear.})
13... Qd7 14. Ng6 $1 Ne7 15. Nxf8 Kxf8 16. f3 Rad8 17. b4 Ng6 18. Nb3 Bc8 19.
Bb1 Nh5 20. axb5 axb5 21. Be3 $16 {Kasparov, G (2805)-Short,N (2655) London
1993 With two bishops and all possible ruptures, White stands clearly better.})
13. Nc4 Rb8 14. Bd2 Bc8 15. h3 d6 16. Ne3 bxc3 17. bxc3 Be6 18. Qc2 Bxa2 19.
Qxa2 Qd7 20. Rab1 $14 {Dominguez Perez,L (2720) -Piorun,K (2681) Monzon ESP
2016}) 12. Bc2 c5 13. d4 exd4 14. cxd4 d5 15. e5 Ne4 16. axb5 $1 {This a key
improvement for the line} axb5 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Rxe4 $1 Nb3 $2 (18... Nc4 {
is better} 19. Rxa8 Bxa8 20. Rg4 $14) 19. Rxa8 Bxa8 20. Ng5 {with a decisive
attack. White won in just a few more moves} Nxc1 21. Qh5 h6 22. Qxf7+ Kh8 23.
Rg4 Qa5 24. h4 {1-0 (24) Anand,V (2762)-Svidler,P (2757) Moscow RUS 2016}) 10.
Nbd2 {Following the usual plan - Nd2-Nf1-Ng3.} Na5 {This is the standard idea
for Black but there are a lot of other possibilities. Let's have a look at the
most important ones.} (10... Nd7 11. c3 Nc5 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Bxa8 14. Bc2
Bf6 15. b4 Ne6 16. Nf1 Bb7 17. Ne3 g6 18. Bb3 Bg7 19. h4 Bc8 20. h5 $14 {
Kasparov,G (2805)-Short,N (2655) London 1993}) (10... Qd7 {with the idea of
Nd8-e6.} 11. c3 $5 {I prefer to delay the knight transfer to g3} (11. Nf1 Nd8
12. Ng3 Ne6 13. c3 c5 14. d4 exd4 15. cxd4 d5 $132) 11... Rfe8 (11... Nd8 12.
d4 {is the idea}) 12. Nf1 h6 (12... Nd8 13. Ng3 Ne6 14. d4) 13. Ng3 Na5 14. Bc2
c5 15. d4 Bf8 16. d5 c4 17. Be3 Qc7 18. Nd2 Bc8 19. h3 Bd7 20. Qf3 $14 Be7 21.
Ra2 Reb8 22. axb5 axb5 23. Rea1 Qd8 24. Nf5 $14 {Topalov,V (2735)-Adams,M 
(2720) Wijk aan Zee 2004}) (10... Nb8 {in Breyer style} 11. axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8
Bxa8 13. Nf1 Nbd7 14. Ng3 Nc5 (14... g6 $2 15. Bh6 Re8 16. Ng5 d5 17. exd5 Bxd5
18. c4 $1 $16) 15. Ba2 Bb7 16. Bd2 (16. Nf5 Bc8 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 18. c3 Be6 19.
Bb1 Ra8 20. d4 $14 {1-0 (40) Adhiban,B (2567) -Bailet,P (2474) Barcelona 2013})
16... Qd7 17. Nf5 Ra8 18. Qb1 Ne6 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. b4 $14 {Wei Yi (2718)-Wen
Yang (2583) Xinghua CHN 2015}) (10... Re8 11. Nf1 {The play does not vary much
from the standard Ruy Lopez. White will continue next with c2-c3 or Ng3 and
will wait for the right moment to play d3-d4. Another idea is to play on the
kingside. However, if Black plays} Bf8 {then he has the interesting option of}
(11... h6 {could be a solution to stop the pin with Bg5 but I like the
following idea played by Svidler} 12. Bd2 Bf8 13. c4 $5 {13.Ng3 13.Ne3 and
even 13.h3 with the idea of Nh2-g4 are all interesting} b4 (13... bxc4 14. Bxc4
Rb8 15. Bc3 Ne7 16. Ng3 Ng6 17. d4 exd4 18. Qxd4 d5 19. exd5 Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1
Nxd5 21. Rd1 $14 {Kasparov,G (2849)-Tkachiev,V (2672) Cannes 2001}) 14. a5 Nd7
15. Ba4 Rb8 16. Ne3 Nc5 17. Qc2 b3 18. Qc3 $14 {Grischuk,A (2668)-Tkachiev,V 
(2672) Enghien les Bains 2001 I like White's position here because of his
control over d5.}) 12. Bg5 $5 {which has been employed by Anand and Adams and
I like it a lot because it leads to quiet positions when everything is under
control. For example:} h6 (12... Nb8 13. axb5 axb5 14. Rxa8 Bxa8 15. Qa1 Bb7 (
15... Nbd7 {but then} 16. Qa2 $1 Qe7 17. Ng3 g6 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Ng5 $1 d5 20.
Bxd5 Bxd5 21. Qxd5 $16) 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Ne3 c6 18. Nh4 Na6 19. Qd1 {and
white had a winning position. Adams,M (2682)-Matlakov,M (2574) Montcada 2009})
13. Bh4 Na5 14. Ba2 c5 15. Ne3 b4 16. Nd2 Bc8 17. Qf3 Be6 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19.
Qxf6 gxf6 20. Bd5 $16 {Anand,V (2779)-Zoler,D (2455) Rishon Le Ziyyon 2006
White had control over the light squares and went on to win}) (10... b4 11. a5
Rb8 12. Bc4 (12. Nc4 $5 Bc8 13. Ba4 Bd7 14. c3 $14) 12... h6 13. Nf1 Re8 14.
Ne3 Bf8 15. Bd2 Qd7 {Lutz,C (2555)-Almasi,Z (2595) Germany 1997} 16. Bb3 {
would have kept some pressure. The idea of Ba4 is annoying for Black.}) 11. Ba2
c5 12. Nf1 {This is an interesting idea. White saves the tempo and skips the
move c2-c3 for the moment.} b4 {In my opinion, this is the strongest move for
Black.} (12... bxa4 $5 {has been played by Tomashevsky with success} 13. Ne3
Bc8 (13... Bc6 {is an important alternative here} 14. Bd2 (14. Nh4 $5) 14...
Bd7 15. Bb1 $5 Qc7 16. b3 Rfb8 17. bxa4 Nc6 18. Ba2 Be6 19. Bc4 (19. Bxe6 fxe6
20. Nc4 {is slightly more pleasant for White. Note that is difficult for Black
to play d6-d5.}) 19... Bxc4 20. Nxc4 {Black is only a tiny worse. The
following correspondence game shows that Black can hold but White's play seems
easier to me which is all that matters.} Ra7 21. Bg5 Rab7 22. Nfd2 Bd8 23. g3
Nd7 24. Bxd8 Nxd8 25. c3 Nc6 26. Qc2 g6 27. Rab1 Kg7 28. Rxb7 Rxb7 29. Rb1
Rxb1+ 30. Qxb1 Na5 31. h4 Nxc4 32. Nxc4 Qc6 33. a5 d5 {1/2-1/2 (33) Betker,J 
(2452)-Krzyzanowski,D (2461) ICCF 2016}) 14. Nh4 $1 g6 15. Nf3 Bd7 16. Nd5 Nxd5
17. Bxd5 Rb8 18. Bh6 Re8 19. Qd2 Bc6 20. Bxc6 Nxc6 21. c3 Qd7 22. Qc2 a5 23.
Rxa4 {The position is roughly equal but White has a better pawn structure.}
Red8 24. Bc1 d5 25. exd5 Qxd5 26. Rae4 f6 27. Qa4 Rbc8 28. R4e3 Rc7 29. Nd2
Rcd7 30. Nc4 $14 {and eventually White won in Giri,A (2776)-Tomashevsky,E 
(2749) Khanty-Mansiysk RUS 2015}) 13. c3 bxc3 14. bxc3 c4 (14... Rb8 15. Ne3
Bc8 16. d4 Qc7 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Nc4 Nd7 19. Nfd2 Nxc4 20. Nxc4 Nb6 21. Ne3 $14
{was a bit better for White Vachier Lagrave,M (2713) -Stefanova,A (2516)
Caleta ENG 2013.}) 15. Ng3 cxd3 16. Qxd3 Bc8 (16... Nd7 {did not turn out well
for Black since he is not in time to coordinate his forces.} 17. Be3 g6 18.
Rab1 Bc6 19. Bh6 Re8 20. Qd2 $1 {with the threat of Ng5} Bf8 21. Bxf7+ {
a shocking sacrifice but not really necessary at all.} (21. Bxf8 Nxf8 22. Qh6 {
would have been very strong with ideas like Ng5 or Nh4 followed by Re3}) 21...
Kxf7 22. Qa2+ Ke7 23. Ng5 Qc7 $4 (23... Qc8 $1 {and Black escapes!}) 24. Qe6+ {
1-0 (24) Naiditsch,A (2685)-Fedorchuk,S (2643) Sibenik 2009}) 17. Ba3 Qc7 18.
Red1 Nb7 19. Qc4 Qxc4 20. Bxc4 Re8 21. Rab1 Ra7 22. Rb6 Na5 23. Bf1 Nd7 24.
Rbb1 Nc5 25. Bxc5 dxc5 26. Nxe5 $16 {Even though Black managed to hold the
draw in Svidler,P (2765) -Ivanchuk,V (2729) Morelia/ Linares 2006 Conclusion:
It is nearly impossible to examine all the variations of this line but
following the ideas shown above is enough to keep oriented in this type of
positions. In classical openings like the Spanish, both sides can choose one
move or another, without making a significant change of the character of the
positions.} *

