1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. a4
b4 9. a5 $1 {Of course, this move is nothing new but it has been employed by
Wesley So and Caruana and it seems to me this is the most direct way to handle
this position.} d6 (9... d5 {is always critical. After} 10. exd5 {and now:}
Nxd5 {,I'd like to point out a rare continuation which I find promising for
White.} (10... e4 11. dxc6 exf3 12. d4 fxg2 13. Nd2 Be6 (13... Bg4 14. Nf3 {
the pin is awkward but White will come out with Qd3 next.}) 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15.
Rxe6 $14 {This idea needs practical test. I think White is slightly better.})
11. d3 $5 {with the idea of simply developing the knight to d2 where it has
great squares like e4 or c4.} (11. Nxe5 {has been the main move here} Nxe5 12.
Rxe5 {We have obtained a favorable version of Marshall since the inclusion of
the moves a4-a5 for White and b5-b4 for Black considerably weakens Black's
queenside.}) 11... Bf6 {is an ugly way to defend the pawn and now simply} (
11... Bg4 12. Nbd2 f6 {does not really work because white has a hidden tactic}
13. h3 Bh5 $2 14. Nxe5 Bxd1 15. Nxc6 Qd7 16. Nxe7+ Kh8 17. Bxd5 Bxc2 18. Re4 $3
{threatening mate in two} Qe8 19. Bc4 {White is winning.}) 12. Nbd2 Be6 13. Ne4
{looks better for White. This continuation is unexplored and I don't expect
many games in it to be honest, mostly because of the fact that the line looks
grim for Black.}) 10. d3 {White wants Nbd2 followed by Nc4 with a nice outpost
for the knight and a full control of the center. Therefore, Black is in a
hurry to trade the light-squared bishop.} Be6 (10... Bg4 {can be answered
either by} 11. Nbd2 ({or c3.} 11. c3) 11... Nd4 12. Bc4 {followed by c3. In
both cases, the bishop on g4 seems misplaced.}) 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Nbd2 Rb8 {
with the idea of Rb5 and win the pawn on a5. Black can also try other moves} (
12... d5 {is possible but the problem is that this central structure is not as
flexible as one may think at first sight} 13. Nb3 $146 {I like this idea since
it prevents the black bishop from going to a more active square. Our plan may
be Qe2 and Be3, keeping the central tension. It is worth saying that Black
can't take on e4 because his structure becomes very weak.} (13. exd5 exd5 14.
Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Bc5 {Black is very active here, so it's best to decline the
pawn.}) (13. c3 $5 {was Topalov's choice} Bd6 ({I would be more worried here
about} 13... Bc5 $5 14. Nb3 Ba7 15. Bg5 Qd6 {when I thinkBlack is active and
there is certain risk.}) 14. d4 bxc3 15. bxc3 exd4 16. cxd4 dxe4 17. Nxe4 Bb4
18. Bd2 Nxe4 19. Rxe4 Qd5 20. Bxb4 $1 $14 {1-0 (28) Topalov, V (2761)-Svidler,
P (2751) Saint Louis USA 2016}) 13... dxe4 $6 14. Ng5 $14 Qd7 15. dxe4 $1 $14)
(12... Qe8 $5 {saves a tempo and accelerates the attack on the kingside} 13. c3
{White is advised to start playing in the center as soon as possible.} (13. Nb3
Qg6 {with the idea of Rf7-Raf8 looks solid for Black.}) 13... Rb8 {there is
nothing better than transposing to Carlsen - Aronian mentioned in the next
comment.} (13... Qg6 14. Qa4 $1)) 13. Nb3 {White has another interesting way
to play here as shown by Magnus Carlsen} (13. c3 Qe8 14. Nc4 Qg6 15. h3 Nd7 16.
Be3 d5 (16... Rb5 $5 17. Ncd2 {followed by Qe2 I like White's position since
he has a better pawn structure.}) 17. Ncd2 bxc3 18. bxc3 Nc5 19. Bxc5 Bxc5 20.
Qa4 {Carlsen,M (2822)-Aronian,L (2809) Saint Louis 2017}) 13... Qc8 {It is
also logical to activate the queen to the kingside via e8 but White has an
strong response to that.} (13... Qe8 $6 14. d4 $1 exd4 15. Nbxd4 Nxd4 16. Nxd4
Qd7 (16... Qf7 {is perhaps slightly better} 17. Qe2 Nxe4 18. Nc6 Rbe8 19. f3
Nc5 20. Nxb4 {with a better position}) 17. Qe2 c5 18. Nf3 e5 $2 (18... Rb5 19.
e5 $16) 19. Bg5 (19. Qxa6 $18 {should also work}) 19... Qb5 20. Nd2 $16 {
So,W (2808) -Gozzoli,Y (2583) chess.com INT 2017}) 14. h3 $146 {The first new
move of this game} (14. Qe2 Nd8 15. d4 exd4 16. Nbxd4 c5 17. Nb3 e5 18. Nbd2
Ne6 {Caruana,F (2807) -Carlsen,M (2822) Saint Louis 2017}) 14... Nd8 (14... Nd7
15. Be3 {and comeback with Nbd2 next} Nd8 16. Nbd2 c5 17. c3 {and maybe d4 soon
}) 15. Be3 c5 16. Nbd2 Nc6 17. c3 Rb5 18. d4 {A very strong idea by Wesley So,
sacrificing the a5-pawn. The problem for Black is that after taking the pawn,
it is not so simple to coordinate the pieces well. That being said, the
position is still roughly equal.} exd4 {Let's see some of the alternatives
black had at this critical point} (18... bxc3 19. bxc3 exd4 20. cxd4 c4 (20...
cxd4 21. Nxd4 Nxd4 22. Bxd4 Nd7 23. Qe2 Ne5 24. Reb1 {looks slightly better
for White.}) 21. Nxc4 Nxe4 22. Nb6 Qb7 23. d5 exd5 24. Nxd5 Bd8 25. Qd3 {
looks slightly more pleasant for White because of Black's weaknesses.}) (18...
Nxa5 $2 19. dxe5 dxe5 20. c4 {wins on the spot}) 19. cxd4 Nxa5 20. dxc5 dxc5
21. Ra2 $1 {White is a pawn down but now he prepares to put pressure on the
a-file. I can't really say for sure that this is objectively better for White
but it seems that Black has practical problems.} Qb7 (21... Nc6 22. Qe2 $1 {
with similar ideas to the game, Rc1 or Ra1}) (21... Nd7 {is the engine's choice
} 22. Qe2 Nb8 23. Ne5 Nbc6 24. Nxc6 Qxc6 25. Rea1 Bd8 {with equality}) 22. b3
Kh8 23. Qc2 $1 $16 {Simple chess. The threat is now to bring the rook to a1.}
Nd7 24. Rea1 Bd8 25. Nc4 Nxc4 26. Qxc4 Bf6 (26... a5 $2 27. Rd1 $1 $18 {
and Black is dead lost as Rad2 comes next.}) 27. Rd1 Qc6 28. Rad2 Nb6 (28...
Ne5 29. Nxe5 Bxe5 30. Rd8 {is extremely unpleasant} Rb8 31. Rxf8+ Rxf8 32. Bxc5
$16) 29. Qc2 Qc7 $6 30. e5 $16 Be7 31. Nd4 Rc8 32. Nxe6 $1 (32. Nxb5 {should
also be better for White. For example:} axb5 33. Qe4 Nd5 34. Rxd5 exd5 35. Rxd5
c4 36. bxc4 bxc4 37. e6 Qc6 (37... c3 $4 38. Rh5 $18) 38. Bc5 $3 Bxc5 39. Rd8+
Rxd8 40. Qxc6 Bf8 41. Qb7 Re8 42. Qf7 Rc8 43. e7 Bxe7 44. Qxe7 b3 45. Qb7 Rf8
46. Kf1 {White should win.}) 32... Qxe5 33. Nf4 Rf8 34. Re2 Qc3 35. Qb1 $1 Qf6
36. Bc1 $1 {After this move, the outcome of the game is pretty much decided.
White has a very strong attack and Aronian can't avoid losing material.} c4 37.
bxc4 Nxc4 38. Re6 Qg5 39. Ng6+ Qxg6 40. Rxg6 hxg6 41. Qe4 Bf6 42. Qxc4 b3 43.
Ba3 Rfb8 44. Rb1 b2 45. h4 $18 Ra5 46. Qd3 Rd8 47. Qb3 Rc8 48. Qb7 Rd8 49. Qb3
Rc8 50. Qb4 Rb5 51. Qg4 Rc3 52. Bxb2 Rxb2 53. Rxb2 Rc1+ 54. Kh2 Bxb2 55. Qxg6
Ra1 56. g4 a5 57. Qh5+ Kg8 58. Qb5 Ba3 59. Qe5 Rd1 60. Qe6+ Kh7 61. Qe4+ Kh8
62. Qa8+ Kh7 63. Qxa5 Bd6+ 64. Kg2 Rd4 65. Qf5+ Kh8 66. Qh5+ Kg8 67. g5 Kf8 68.
Qg6 Be7 69. Qf5+ Ke8 70. Kh3 Rd6 71. Qh7 Kf7 72. f4 Rd4 73. Qf5+ Ke8 74. Qe5
Rb4 75. Kg4 Kf8 76. Qf5+ Ke8 77. Qe6 Rd4 78. Qe5 {1-0 (78) So,W (2799)-Aronian,
L (2794) Berlin GER 2018} *

